        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I looked around GitHub and found several plugins that show the output of an external command or LLM as virtual lines after manually wrapping them. When a buffer is shown in multiple windows, the manual wrapping may only work for one of them. Such plugins most likely want all output to be always visible, which means they won't want virtual lines to scroll horizontally, and may want them to wrap even with `'nowrap'` so that they won't have to do manual wrapping.\n\nThere are also several plugins that use virtual lines to display separator or filler lines (e.g. [gitsigns.nvim](https://github.com/lewis6991/gitsigns.nvim/blob/4c40357994f386e72be92a46f41fc1664c84c87d/lua/gitsigns/blame.lua#L145), [grug-far.nvim](https://github.com/MagicDuck/grug-far.nvim/blob/3a8690461afac34c0e5bacb0f7b4bc3066aab665/lua/grug-far/render/resultsHeader.lua#L91), [headlines.nvim](https://github.com/lukas-reineke/headlines.nvim/blob/bf17c96a836ea27c0a7a2650ba385a7783ed322e/lua/headlines/init.lua#L318), [nvim-tinygit](https://github.com/chrisgrieser/nvim-tinygit/blob/d0cbd1fd1736d3cf1638eda1d008e7d6d0d842e6/lua/tinygit/shared/diff.lua#L129)). Wrapping and horizontal scrolling are not desired for such virtual lines.\n\n~Therefore [option 2](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/31000#issuecomment-2662303935) seems better here. Plus it's easier to implement two separate flags than to implement one flag that does two things.~",
